Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1276–1330":"circa 1276–1330","1260–Male":"1260–Overleden","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Male":"1270–Overleden","1273–Male":"1273–Overleden","1276–1330":"1276–1330","–Male":"Overleden","1283–1330":"1283–1330","1305–1361":"1305–1361","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1247–1326":"1247–1326","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1247":"1247","3 May 1326":"3 mei 1326","Abt 1276":"circa 1276","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","Kilmartin, Argyll, Scotland":"Kilmartin, Argyll, Schotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Schotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Schotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1276–1330":"about 1276–1330","1260–Male":"1260–Deceased","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Male":"1270–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1276–1330":"1276–1330","–Male":"Deceased","1283–1330":"1283–1330","1305–1361":"1305–1361","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1247–1326":"1247–1326","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1247":"1247","3 May 1326":"3 May 1326","Abt 1276":"about 1276","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","Kilmartin, Argyll, Scotland":"Kilmartin, Argyll, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunningham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunigan","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish or Irish   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Conahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac.","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Connachaín</b> (see   Cunningham  )."]},{"name":"Conaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Fergal.","Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire) Irish (Donegal): from <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b>, see   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cuningham","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cummingham","meanings":["(1997: 117;2007: 199; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cunnigham","meanings":["(2007: 429; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish (Donegal): variant of   Cunningham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Cunningham was born about 1276, his father, Edward de Cunynghame, of Kilmaurs, was 38 and his mother, Mary Stewart, was 30. He had at least 1 son with Richenda de Berkeley. He died in 1330, at the age of 55."},"et":{"Abt 1276–1330":"umbes 1276–1330","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1276–1330":"1276–1330","–Male":"Surnud","1283–1330":"1283–1330","1305–1361":"1305–1361","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1247–1326":"1247–1326","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1273":"1273","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1247":"1247","3 May 1326":"3. mai 1326","Abt 1276":"umbes 1276","1265":"1265","1276":"1276","Kilmartin, Argyll, Scotland":"Kilmartin, Argyll, Scotland","Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lanarkshire, Scotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1276–1330":"noin 1276–1330","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1265–1292":"1265–1292","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1273–Male":"1273–Kuollut","1276–1330":"1276–1330","–Male":"Kuollut","1283–1330":"1283–1330","1305–1361":"1305–1361","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1247–1326":"1247–1326","1330":"1330","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1273":"1273